    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lessons From an F.B.I. Blunder</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ellen Ellender letter holds all citizens should be concerned about whether their civil rights and personal property are adequately protected, in light of FBI 'blunder' in Timothy McVeigh case</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''U.S. Admits Failure to Share Evidence in McVeigh's Trial'' (front page, May 11):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''U.S. Admits Failure to Share Evidence in McVeigh's Trial'' (front page, May 11):</p>
        <p>If the F.B.I., touted as the finest law enforcement agency in the world, can make a blunder of this magnitude in the case that would result in the first federal execution in nearly 40 years, then all of us -- not only those on death row -- should question whether our personal liberty and civil rights are adequately protected under the justice system currently in place in the United States.</p>
        <p>ELLEN ELLENDER  Pine Beach, N.J., May 12, 2001</p>
      </block>
